bug.short_desc: "Timed out waiting for device" intermittent boot fault for BTFS filesystems
bug.cf_doc_type: If docs needed, set a value

long_desc.thetext:
Description of problem: On occasion a PC with 3 drives (1 SSD for the OS and 2 hard disks for data storage) will fail to boot with the error "Timed out waiting for device" for either a BTFS stripe or a BTFS mirror on hard disks. This problem has occurred with multiple kernels through the Fedora 25 production lifetime.
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): Kernel 4.10.9-200 at time of writing. This problem has occurred ever since I first installed Fedora 25 and I update every time I use the PC.
How reproducible: Intermittent. About every 5th boot one of two different BRFS storage pools on identical hard disks will fail after a 1.5 minute time-out.
The 2 hard disks are identically configured and both have two partitions. The first partition contains two parts of a BTFS stripe, while the second two contains two parts of a BTFS mirror. Both BTRFS storage pools have multiple subvolumes. Both hard disks are WD30EFRX Red 3TB drives purchased at the same time (December 2016) and actually have no data on them yet (the media PC is still being built in my limited spare time). As far as I can tell there are no issues with the drives. All hardware in the PC was new as of December 2016.
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Occurs intermittently during system boot (either cold start or reboot). Cause unknown.
Appears to differ from other historic bugs with this symptom. I'm a sysadmin not a developer, but I'd guess that this might be some kind of race condition.
Actual results: Boot fails with an error after a 1.5 minute timeout.

Problem really is intermittent. I've never seen it occur twice on two boots nor have I ever seen it occur for both BTFS storage pools at once - only ever one.
(Also, I realise it's probably not optimal for performance to have a stripe and a mirror across two partitions on the same hard disks, but this is a cheap home PC and an opportunity for me to learn!)

I've built a VM with identical configuration but cannot repeat the problem.
Any suggestions on how I might diagnose the problem on the physical machine?
With the latest kernel I'd not had the problem in a number of reboots. I'd hoped it was gone, but I've just had it occur with both storage pools. :(
Created attachment 1274573 Journal entry illustrating the timeout problem
This has just occurred twice in a row with kernel 4.10.11-200. Once after a cold boot and then immediately after a forced reboot.

This problem seems to have gone away, most likely through kernel/software updates!
The only change I made was that back in May I commented the two mounts of the storage pools themselves, so that only the subvolumes are ever mounted. I enabled them again tonight to retest and after three reboots and a cold boot the problem had not occurred again.
Closing ERRATA (unknown update, probably kernel after 4.10.11-200 FC25)
